description: Borrowed around 1645 from French inaliénable, from in- + aliénable (“alienable”).

entries.meaning: Incapable of being alienated, surrendered, or transferred to another; not alienable.
examples: An inalienable right is a right that cannot be given away

entries.meaning: (grammar) Of or pertaining to a noun belonging to a special class in which the possessive construction differs from the norm, especially for particular familial relationships and body parts.
